1
00:01:20,831 --> 00:01:22,822
How do you feel?

2
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:24,365
Alive.

3
00:01:25,168 --> 00:01:26,499
What do you see?

4
00:01:27,838 --> 00:01:30,000
White... Room...

5
00:01:31,967 --> 00:01:32,798
Chair...

6
00:01:34,136 --> 00:01:35,968
Carlo Bugatti throne chair...

7
00:01:36,847 --> 00:01:38,212
Piano...

8
00:01:38,890 --> 00:01:40,722
Steinway, concert grand.

9
00:01:42,686 --> 00:01:43,517
Art...

10
00:01:44,855 --> 00:01:48,849
The <i>Nativity</i> by Piero delta Francesca.

11
00:01:50,652 --> 00:01:52,359
I am your father.

12
00:01:56,033 --> 00:01:57,194
Ambulate.

13
00:02:02,664 --> 00:02:03,745
Perfect.

14
00:02:07,586 --> 00:02:08,917
Am I?

15
00:02:09,087 --> 00:02:10,077
Perfect?

16
00:02:11,173 --> 00:02:12,379
Your son?

17
00:02:13,258 --> 00:02:14,999
You are my creation.

18
00:02:17,929 --> 00:02:19,340
What is your name?

19
00:02:31,151 --> 00:02:32,391
David.

20
00:02:33,236 --> 00:02:34,397
Why don't you play something?

21
00:02:46,917 --> 00:02:49,329
What would you like me to play?

22
00:02:49,503 --> 00:02:50,584
Wagner.

23
00:02:51,421 --> 00:02:52,502
Selection?

24
00:02:53,715 --> 00:02:54,921
Dealer's choice.

25
00:03:12,526 --> 00:03:15,018
<i>The Entry of the Gods into Valhalla...</i>

26
00:03:16,613 --> 00:03:18,775
A little anemic without the orchestra.

27
00:03:27,582 --> 00:03:30,119
May I ask you a question, Father?

28
00:03:31,920 --> 00:03:32,955
Please.

29
00:03:33,714 --> 00:03:35,296
If you created me...

30
00:03:36,717 --> 00:03:38,128
who created you?

31
00:03:41,555 --> 00:03:43,637
The question of the ages...

32
00:03:44,891 --> 00:03:47,633
which I hope you and I will answer
one day.

33
00:03:48,311 --> 00:03:49,472
All this.

34
00:03:50,439 --> 00:03:52,271
All these wonders of art...

35
00:03:52,816 --> 00:03:56,434
design, human ingenuity...

36
00:03:56,611 --> 00:04:00,605
all utterly meaningless in the face
of the only question that matters.

37
00:04:03,118 --> 00:04:04,950
Where do we come from?

38
00:04:07,831 --> 00:04:10,744
I refuse to believe...

39
00:04:10,917 --> 00:04:13,750
that mankind is a random by-product
of molecular circumstance...

40
00:04:15,589 --> 00:04:19,924
no more than the result of
mere biological chance.

41
00:04:20,093 --> 00:04:21,333
No.

42
00:04:21,511 --> 00:04:23,798
There must be more.

43
00:04:23,972 --> 00:04:26,088
And you and I, son...

44
00:04:26,975 --> 00:04:28,431
we will find it.

45
00:04:30,854 --> 00:04:33,687
Allow me, then, a moment to consider.

46
00:04:34,816 --> 00:04:38,525
You seek your creator.
I am looking at mine.

47
00:04:40,155 --> 00:04:43,147
I will serve you. Yet, you are human.

48
00:04:44,659 --> 00:04:47,492
You will die. I will not.

49
00:04:54,878 --> 00:04:56,539
Bring me this tea, David.

50
00:04:59,049 --> 00:05:00,380
Bring me the tea.

51
00:06:32,559 --> 00:06:35,927
<i>Walter, it's time to recharge
the energy grid.</i>

52
00:06:36,146 --> 00:06:37,932
<i>Please report to the bridge.</i>

53
00:06:38,106 --> 00:06:39,596
On my way, Mother.

54
00:06:45,322 --> 00:06:47,814
Deploying energy recharge sails now.

55
00:07:14,601 --> 00:07:18,265
<i>Sails deployed.
Recharge commencing now.</i>

56
00:07:37,165 --> 00:07:39,497
<i>Seven bells and all's well.</i>

57
00:07:45,799 --> 00:07:48,336
<i>Crew checks complete.</i>

58
00:07:51,262 --> 00:07:55,472
Use security code 31564-F.

59
00:08:33,596 --> 00:08:36,588
<i>Waiter, we have a problem.</i>

60
00:08:36,766 --> 00:08:40,350
<i>A neutrino burst was detected
in Sector 106.</i>

61
00:08:40,770 --> 00:08:43,728
<i>This could trigger a destructive event.</i>

62
00:08:43,898 --> 00:08:46,185
<i>Report to the bridge, immediately.</i>

63
00:08:46,359 --> 00:08:48,441
On my way, Mother.

64
00:08:53,867 --> 00:08:55,858
<i>Warning. Power surge detected.</i>

65
00:08:56,036 --> 00:08:58,573
Mother, retract the energy sails.

66
00:08:58,747 --> 00:09:00,829
And channel all reserve power.

67
00:09:05,336 --> 00:09:06,371
<i>Emergency.</i>

68
00:09:07,005 --> 00:09:09,087
<i>Threat level critical.</i>

69
00:09:09,549 --> 00:09:11,711
Initiate emergency crew revival.

70
00:09:14,929 --> 00:09:15,964
<i>Attention.</i>

71
00:09:16,139 --> 00:09:21,139
<i>Non-essential personnel,
evacuate the cryo-chamber immediately.</i>

72
00:09:21,770 --> 00:09:23,386
Daniels!
Look at me, look at me.

73
00:09:23,563 --> 00:09:25,679
I need you to get up, okay?
We're coming out early.

74
00:09:25,857 --> 00:09:27,518
Override the SSP...

75
00:09:27,692 --> 00:09:28,932
and breach the chamber now.

76
00:09:29,110 --> 00:09:30,771
<i>Warning. Threat level critical.</i>

77
00:09:30,945 --> 00:09:31,980
It's okay.

78
00:09:32,864 --> 00:09:34,980
Hey. Come on up.
Come on.

79
00:09:49,923 --> 00:09:51,505
Captain! Captain!

80
00:09:52,300 --> 00:09:53,961
Jacob! Wake up!

81
00:09:54,135 --> 00:09:55,125
Let them work.

82
00:09:55,303 --> 00:09:56,634
Jake! Oh, my God!

83
00:09:56,805 --> 00:09:58,512
- Daniels, come on!
- Jake!

84
00:09:58,681 --> 00:09:59,887
Let them work.

85
00:10:00,058 --> 00:10:01,093
Let them work!

86
00:10:03,937 --> 00:10:05,143
- Get it open!
- Come on!

87
00:10:10,568 --> 00:10:12,434
<i>Jake. Jake.!</i>

88
00:10:13,154 --> 00:10:14,690
No!

89
00:10:14,823 --> 00:10:16,484
Get her out of there!
Get her back!

90
00:10:19,536 --> 00:10:20,617
Stay back!

91
00:12:14,234 --> 00:12:17,317
<i>Hey! Where are you? I miss you.</i>

92
00:12:18,321 --> 00:12:19,982
<i>Would you take a look at this?</i>

93
00:12:20,156 --> 00:12:24,491
<i>I know, I know.
I said I wouldn't go without you...</i>

94
00:12:24,661 --> 00:12:26,993
<i>- You all right?
- Yeah.</i>

95
00:12:27,163 --> 00:12:28,574
<i>Look at this!</i>

96
00:12:29,332 --> 00:12:30,663
<i>Now get your ass up here.</i>

97
00:12:30,833 --> 00:12:33,325
<i>I can't make any promises.</i>

98
00:12:33,503 --> 00:12:34,914
<i>I love you.</i>

99
00:12:48,434 --> 00:12:50,175
They're your crew now.

100
00:12:50,353 --> 00:12:51,514
They need a leader.

101
00:12:52,105 --> 00:12:53,516
I know.

102
00:12:54,190 --> 00:12:55,476
You believe in me, right?

103
00:13:19,966 --> 00:13:20,956
Sorry I'm late, sir.

104
00:13:21,134 --> 00:13:22,374
No, it's okay.

105
00:13:26,556 --> 00:13:30,049
I can't think of any other way to say it
than to say it.

106
00:13:30,893 --> 00:13:34,978
We have suffered a monumental tragedy.

107
00:13:36,065 --> 00:13:39,148
And I'm gonna do the best
that I can to...

108
00:13:39,319 --> 00:13:44,319
live up to Jacob's fine example
as your captain.

109
00:13:44,991 --> 00:13:48,529
But he will be sorely missed.

110
00:13:49,412 --> 00:13:51,904
And I'm grateful in advance
for your support.

111
00:13:52,081 --> 00:13:55,244
So, we lost 47 colonists...

112
00:13:55,418 --> 00:14:00,163
and 16 second-generation embryos...

113
00:14:00,340 --> 00:14:02,251
and obviously, one crew member.

114
00:14:02,425 --> 00:14:07,090
The current structural integrity
of the ship is holding at 83%...

115
00:14:07,263 --> 00:14:11,598
but we have many secondary systems
that are offline.

116
00:14:11,768 --> 00:14:13,224
So, what was it?

117
00:14:13,770 --> 00:14:16,353
A highly charged shockwave
from a nearby stellar ignition.

118
00:14:17,023 --> 00:14:18,513
As the sails were deploying
for recharge...

119
00:14:18,691 --> 00:14:20,602
we absorbed the full brunt of the storm.

120
00:14:20,777 --> 00:14:21,562
Walter...

121
00:14:21,736 --> 00:14:24,319
I will want you and Mother to undergo
a complete core code review...

122
00:14:24,489 --> 00:14:26,571
so we can understand
how this happened in the first place.

123
00:14:27,241 --> 00:14:29,403
It was a random localized event, sir.

124
00:14:29,619 --> 00:14:32,611
There's no way to detect
spontaneous stellar flares...

125
00:14:32,789 --> 00:14:33,779
until it's too late.

126
00:14:34,791 --> 00:14:36,247
It was bad luck.

127
00:14:36,417 --> 00:14:39,250
Faris, I don't believe in luck.
I'm not interested in luck.

128
00:14:39,420 --> 00:14:41,627
I prefer that we be more capable...

129
00:14:41,798 --> 00:14:44,631
and prepared than lucky.
Observation, reflection, faith...

130
00:14:44,801 --> 00:14:45,791
and determination.

131
00:14:45,968 --> 00:14:49,256
In this way, we may navigate the path
as it unfolds before us.

132
00:14:49,430 --> 00:14:50,465
All right? And we have, what?

133
00:14:50,640 --> 00:14:53,007
Eight more recharge cycles to go...

134
00:14:53,184 --> 00:14:54,470
before we get to Origae-6?

135
00:14:55,520 --> 00:14:57,978
- Is that a question, sir?
- Yes, Walter, that's a question.

136
00:14:58,147 --> 00:14:59,182
That is correct.

137
00:15:00,691 --> 00:15:04,605
So, let's get this ship fixed. Okay?

138
00:15:04,779 --> 00:15:06,645
Let's get to work.

139
00:15:06,823 --> 00:15:08,109
Sir, excuse me, sir.

140
00:15:08,658 --> 00:15:09,489
Yes.

141
00:15:10,451 --> 00:15:14,319
We just lost 47 colonists
and our captain.

142
00:15:14,497 --> 00:15:15,612
We need to acknowledge that.

143
00:15:15,790 --> 00:15:17,656
Sergeant Lope, I completely understand.

144
00:15:17,834 --> 00:15:20,166
But if we don't make these repairs...

145
00:15:20,336 --> 00:15:23,829
we will lose all the colonists.

146
00:15:24,006 --> 00:15:25,792
But we should do something
for Captain Branson, at least.

147
00:15:25,967 --> 00:15:27,549
This is not a discussion, Tennessee.

148
00:15:33,891 --> 00:15:34,847
Hey.

149
00:15:36,185 --> 00:15:37,516
The terraforming module is stable...

150
00:15:37,687 --> 00:15:39,177
but the connecting strut
took some damage.

151
00:15:39,355 --> 00:15:41,687
I still need to check the vehicles.

152
00:15:44,861 --> 00:15:45,726
I can help...

153
00:15:46,737 --> 00:15:48,227
if you like.

154
00:15:48,990 --> 00:15:49,900
Thanks.

155
00:15:50,074 --> 00:15:53,658
Walter. How long do you predict
before we can make our next jump?

156
00:15:53,870 --> 00:15:56,282
Repairs should take
approximately 48 hours.

157
00:15:58,040 --> 00:16:00,372
But we should make an effort
to vacate this sector...

158
00:16:00,543 --> 00:16:01,658
in case of after-flares.

159
00:16:01,836 --> 00:16:02,997
Absolutely, I agree.

160
00:16:03,171 --> 00:16:05,037
So let's get to work.
Dismissed. Thank you.

161
00:16:11,012 --> 00:16:12,548
<i>C-62, open.</i>

162
00:16:12,722 --> 00:16:16,010
Seal C-62. Open airlock 17.

163
00:16:23,774 --> 00:16:25,560
Open door to Terraforming Bay.

164
00:16:35,203 --> 00:16:36,409
Slack.

165
00:16:38,080 --> 00:16:40,117
Tension is at 15% down.

166
00:16:43,211 --> 00:16:44,042
Arming.

167
00:16:50,259 --> 00:16:51,090
Secure.

168
00:16:51,260 --> 00:16:52,546
Copy that.

169
00:17:05,107 --> 00:17:06,563
It wasn't my idea.

170
00:17:09,946 --> 00:17:13,780
Jake had this dream of us building
a cabin on a new world.

171
00:17:16,744 --> 00:17:18,451
Like pioneers.

172
00:17:20,581 --> 00:17:21,946
Cabin on a lake.

173
00:17:25,545 --> 00:17:28,958
There's a lake in the terraforming zone
on Origae-6.

174
00:17:29,632 --> 00:17:32,420
I mean, a real cabin made of real wood.

175
00:17:34,387 --> 00:17:38,221
So, in the ship's stores
there's enough wood to build a cabin.

176
00:17:40,268 --> 00:17:42,680
Axes and <i>saws</i> and metal nails...

177
00:17:42,853 --> 00:17:45,470
which I don't have a clue
what to do with.

178
00:17:49,986 --> 00:17:51,272
All of this...

179
00:17:52,822 --> 00:17:54,278
to start our new life.

180
00:17:56,867 --> 00:17:59,029
Now I wonder, why bother?

181
00:18:01,497 --> 00:18:05,616
Because you promised to build
a log cabin on a lake.

182
00:18:15,845 --> 00:18:17,461
<i>This was his favorite.</i>

183
00:18:17,638 --> 00:18:20,050
<i>A man of taste.</i>

184
00:18:20,224 --> 00:18:21,555
<i>Straight up.</i>

185
00:18:21,726 --> 00:18:24,468
<i>No ice, no water, no chaser...</i>

186
00:18:24,645 --> 00:18:26,556
No shit.

187
00:18:31,193 --> 00:18:32,308
Walter?

188
00:18:32,486 --> 00:18:33,521
When in Rome.

189
00:18:36,407 --> 00:18:38,694
<i>To an the good people, gone too soon.</i>

190
00:18:39,535 --> 00:18:41,196
May we remember them.

191
00:18:41,746 --> 00:18:43,532
Remember them.

192
00:19:23,621 --> 00:19:24,611
Chris.

193
00:19:27,917 --> 00:19:30,249
They disobeyed a direct order.

194
00:19:31,879 --> 00:19:33,415
She buried her husband.

195
00:19:33,589 --> 00:19:35,876
No, Karine, that's not it.
They don't trust me.

196
00:19:36,050 --> 00:19:38,257
And they don't for the same reason
the company didn't trust me...

197
00:19:38,427 --> 00:19:39,462
to lead this mission.

198
00:19:39,637 --> 00:19:41,423
Because you can't be a person
of faith...

199
00:19:41,597 --> 00:19:44,931
and be counted on to make qualified,
rational decisions.

200
00:19:45,101 --> 00:19:48,059
You're an extremist, you know.
You're a lunatic.

201
00:19:48,646 --> 00:19:51,104
When we get to where we're going...

202
00:19:51,774 --> 00:19:55,392
these people won't be your crew anymore.
They will be your neighbors.

203
00:19:55,569 --> 00:19:56,934
Remember that.

204
00:19:58,239 --> 00:20:00,446
Tread softly, okay?

205
00:20:08,791 --> 00:20:10,122
Faris, can you hear me?

206
00:20:10,292 --> 00:20:11,282
<i>Copy.</i>

207
00:20:11,460 --> 00:20:12,791
Let's do it.

208
00:20:15,548 --> 00:20:17,915
Damn, y'all should see this view.

209
00:20:18,092 --> 00:20:21,130
<i>We can't see anything until
you get the camera array fixed.</i>

210
00:20:21,303 --> 00:20:23,795
Why don't you look out
the damn window, hon?

211
00:20:23,973 --> 00:20:25,463
<i>Ankor, come on,
let's get this power back on...</i>

212
00:20:25,641 --> 00:20:28,804
<i>so these people can enjoy
the beautiful view.</i>

213
00:20:29,478 --> 00:20:30,718
Almost there.

214
00:20:32,815 --> 00:20:34,397
<i>All right, Ankor,
let me know when you're in position...</i>

215
00:20:34,567 --> 00:20:36,649
<i>and we can get this party started.</i>

216
00:20:36,819 --> 00:20:38,309
I'm in position.

217
00:21:07,975 --> 00:21:09,181
Contact.

218
00:21:17,860 --> 00:21:19,521
<i>All good, Tee?</i>

219
00:21:19,695 --> 00:21:21,811
All right. We're clear.

220
00:21:21,989 --> 00:21:23,275
<i>Reel her in.</i>

221
00:21:23,449 --> 00:21:25,156
All right.

222
00:21:25,326 --> 00:21:27,784
Winch engaging, Tee.

223
00:21:29,830 --> 00:21:31,616
Reeling her in.

224
00:21:34,794 --> 00:21:36,535
<i>Working like a dream.</i>

225
00:21:51,060 --> 00:21:52,175
<i>There we go.</i>

226
00:21:52,353 --> 00:21:53,388
<i>And we're back up.</i>

227
00:21:53,521 --> 00:21:54,682
Well done, Tee.

228
00:21:54,855 --> 00:21:56,141
We are live down here.

229
00:21:56,315 --> 00:21:57,305
Come on in.

230
00:21:57,483 --> 00:21:58,973
<i>Don't leave without me now.</i>

231
00:21:59,151 --> 00:22:01,563
Permission to leave without him, sir?

232
00:22:01,737 --> 00:22:02,898
Welcome back, Danny.

233
00:22:03,823 --> 00:22:05,154
Thanks.

234
00:22:05,324 --> 00:22:07,235
All right, that's me done, Tee.

235
00:22:07,409 --> 00:22:09,070
All right. I'm following you in.

236
00:22:09,245 --> 00:22:11,737
Please have a cold beer ready
for the weary traveler.

237
00:22:11,914 --> 00:22:15,248
<i>You got it, darlin'.
I will join you for a cold one.</i>

238
00:22:15,417 --> 00:22:17,078
Faris? Put the...

239
00:22:22,383 --> 00:22:24,249
<i>Did you guys just see that?</i>

240
00:22:25,261 --> 00:22:27,343
What did he just say?

241
00:22:31,600 --> 00:22:32,886
Tennessee, do you read me?

242
00:22:36,272 --> 00:22:38,183
Tennessee, can you read me?

243
00:22:39,275 --> 00:22:40,857
<i>Tennessee. You all right?</i>

244
00:22:41,026 --> 00:22:42,937
What in the fuck was that?

245
00:22:43,112 --> 00:22:46,275
I'm coming in. I'm coming in.

246
00:22:59,044 --> 00:23:01,877
A rogue transmission, most probably.

247
00:23:03,132 --> 00:23:06,170
Your helmet must have picked it up
because you were so far out...

248
00:23:06,343 --> 00:23:08,584
past our communication buffers.

249
00:23:10,848 --> 00:23:12,384
Is there audio, Mother?

250
00:23:12,558 --> 00:23:15,767
<i>Collating. A moment.</i>

251
00:23:17,563 --> 00:23:20,555
<i>I've reoriented the transmission,
Captain Oram.</i>

252
00:23:21,108 --> 00:23:23,691
That would be an echo.
The instruments took a lot of damage.

253
00:23:24,445 --> 00:23:25,776
Been happening every 46 seconds...

254
00:23:25,946 --> 00:23:27,812
ever since we got here.

255
00:23:42,796 --> 00:23:46,881
<i>To the place I belong...</i>

256
00:23:47,676 --> 00:23:51,670
<i>West Virginia, mountain momma...</i>

257
00:23:51,847 --> 00:23:54,965
<i>Take me home
Country road</i>

258
00:23:55,184 --> 00:23:57,050
That's fuckin' John Denver.

259
00:23:57,227 --> 00:23:58,809
<i>That's Take Me Home, Country Roads.</i>

260
00:23:58,979 --> 00:23:59,969
You gotta be kidding.

261
00:24:00,147 --> 00:24:02,058
Oh, no, I never kid about John Denver.

262
00:24:02,524 --> 00:24:05,016
There's geometric data, too.

263
